GM!!!!!!!! Giving some updates to the community here as to why the system was broken over the weekend

1. We believe that operations interfacing with R2 cloudflare are leading to slow downs on the orchestrator side, as we are doing many operations to ensure data validity. We are taking stock of the entire R2 pipeline today to ensure that we aren't doing anything unnecessary, and optimizing anything that is too slow

2. There are potential edge cases with orchestrator level caching. Endpoints that miners call are cached in such a way that if the orchestrator needs to make a call to the db, we cache this endpoint *locally* to the orch. However, this of course could lead to some misalignment in what each orchestrator sees on the order of 1-2 seconds. We are implementing a global redis layer to have horizontally scaled caching (https://github.com/redis/redis)

messages.content: Quite a bit noiser earlier in training. The spikes you see in earlier in training are caused by the outer optimizer (Nesterov). We think local pseudo gradients have different direction and averaging them early in training just overshoots to a new unexplored direction. The outer optimizer takes care of that later, from what @CryptAL says

So we are exploring DiloCo as a way to accelerate training on IOTA. Currently, we are averaging and communicating weights and optimizer states after 500 total backwards. This is obviously a huge hit on the training speed. DiloCo will allow us to perform up to 50K total backwards before performing a global step. Also the volume communicated in that global step will be less than half what we currently communicate. This is a 500x speedup wrt. to our current training. We are currently validating how DiloCo behaves with our modified bottleneck-Llama architecture
